In [[religion]], according to the [[Book of Mormon]] '''Himni''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|h|ɪ|m|n|aɪ}})<ref>[http://www.lds.org/scriptures/bofm/pronunciation?lang=eng LDS.org: "Book of Mormon Pronunciation Guide"] (retrieved 2012-02-25), [[Wikipedia:IPA for English|IPA]]-ified from «hĭm´nī»</ref> was a [[Nephite]] missionary and one of the sons of [[King Mosiah I|King Mosiah]], and brother to the prophet [[Ammon (Book of Mormon)|Ammon]].  According to the Book, Himni and his three brothers Ammon, [[Omner]], and [[Aaron (Nephite)|Aaron]] left their father, and his people, to travel to the land of the [[Lamanites]] in order to preach the gospel to them.<ref>{{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=17|verse=6-8}}</ref>
During their sojourn there, Himni was imprisoned and beaten,<ref>{{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=26|verse=29}}</ref> but eventually aided in the conversion of thousands of Lamanites, who later became the [[Anti-Nephi-Lehi]]s.<ref>{{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Alma|chapter=23|}}</ref>

