==Career== ===Early career=== Prior to founding Groundswell, Will worked in journalism at ''Der Spiegel'' as well as the [[American Academy in Berlin]], Germany, before joining [[Barack Obama]]’s 2008 Presidential campaign.<ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/champions/green-energy/william-byrne "Champions of Change: William Byrne"] Whitehouse.gov</ref>
===Obama for America=== During his work on President Obama's 2008 Campaign, Will utilized online and offline community organizing tactics. While doing this work, Byrne and his co-founders saw the impact of community organizing in the political sphere.<ref>[http://grist.org/renewable-energy/power-in-numbers-crowd-purchasing-brings-clean-energy-within-reach/ "Power in Numbers: Crowd Purchasing Brings Clean Energy Within Reach"] ''Grist'', Retrieved on 16 May 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.blogtalkradio.com/soulful-green-living/2012/03/21/brett-wiley-of-groundswell-2 "The Evolution of a Green Organization"] BlogTalkRadio, Retrieved on 21 March 2012</ref> Rather than joining the administration after Obama was elected, Will went on to develop these tactics as a [[social entrepreneur]].<ref>[http://www.washingtonlife.com/2011/05/19/whos-next-will-byrne/ "Who’s Next: Will Byrne"] ''Washington Life'', Retrieved on 19 May 2011</ref>
===Groundswell=== In 2009, Will, Max Harper, Marcus Ryan, John Lauer, Kristen Psaki, and Tony Ficarotta co-founded [[Groundswell (organization)|Groundswell]] after working on President Obama’s 2008 campaign. Groundswell is a non-profit organization based in Washington, D.C. that uses [[collective buying power]] to drive positive social change, especially in the [[clean energy]] sector.<ref>[http://capitolfile-magazine.com/personalities/articles/dc-hotshots-on-the-evolution-of-cool-in-washington#Will%20Byrne "The Evolution of Cool in DC. Will Byrne: Socially Conscious CEO"] ''Capitol File'' magazine, Retrieved on 1 June 2014</ref>
=== Stanford Design School === In 2015 Will joined the Stanford Design School as a Civic Innovation Fellow.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Will Byrne|url = http://whiteboard.stanford.edu/will-byrne|website = The Whiteboard|accessdate = 2015-12-28}}</ref>
==Honors and awards== *Forbes 30 Under 30 Selection; Social Entrepreneurs, Forbes Magazine (December 2012) <ref>[https://www.forbes.com/pictures/ekeg45kfk/will-byrne-28/ "Forbes 30 Under 30"] Forbes, Retrieved on 17 December 2012</ref> *Global Fellow, Ashoka Innovators for the Public, December 2011 <ref>[https://www.ashoka.org/fellow/will-byrne "Will Byrne"]</ref> *Global Shaper, [[World Economic Forum]], 2011 *Champions of Change, White House Executive Office of the President, 2011 <ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/champions/green-energy/william-byrne "Champions of Change: William Byrne"] Whitehouse.gov</ref><ref>[http://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2011/04/13/champions-change-harnessing-power-community-and-clean-energy "Champions of Change: Harnessing the Power of Community and Clean Energy"] White House Blog, Retrieved 13 April 2011</ref> *Young Atlanticist Network, [[Atlantic Council]], January 2014 *Cordes Social Entrepreneurship Fellow (Global), 2010 *Lisa B. Hall Fellow, [[Concord Academy]], 2013 <ref>[http://www.concordacademy.org/about_concord_academy/hallfellowship.aspx "Hall Fellowship"]</ref>
